<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-090-016 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 134 695</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Shopper  August 1991 v11 n8 p111(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>PCs for peanuts: how to buy computers for under $100. (Trends andamp;Technology)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Topic:     BooksMicrocomputersDiscountComputer RetailingPurchases.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Yes, you too can find brandname/generic clone systems and peripherals forless than $100.andM;Sound like a snake oil story? Not quite, but it will require a bit of legworkto land a steal.andM;A new guide, &quot;How to Buy a Computer for Under $100,&quot; tells you where to look,who to contact, and what to avoid when searing for a bargain PC, printer, orother peripheral.andM;The author, Billy Carlisle, found nearly 50 sources for inexpensive equipmentwhile searching for a PC to use at home.andP;  Most of the bargain-basement-pricedsystems Carlisle happened upon were rudimentary, used systems -- XTs, ATs.andO;PS/2s, and Apples from the lower-end of the price scale.andP;  Surprisingly, newsystems are also available via liquidation sales of manufacturer'sdiscontinued models.andM;The lowest prices are usually found at junkyards: leftovers from eithermanufacturers that have gone out of business, or businesses that purchasednew equipment and dumped the old at a salvage yard.andM;&quot;Sometimes it's hard to find [good equipment], but it's an option to try whenyou're searching,&quot; Carlisle added, &quot;because often that's where you'll findthe lowest price.&quot;andM;&quot;How to Buy a Computer for Under $100&quot; is available from CoastalCommunications, 3700 Carlyle Close, Suite 850, Dept.andP;  003CM, Mobile, AL36609.andO;</TEXT></DOC>